<p>Phytocannabinoids are mainly produced in glandular hairs called trichomes [
 <xref rid="B99-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">99</xref>,
 <xref rid="B100-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">100</xref>,
 <xref rid="B101-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">101</xref>,
 <xref rid="B102-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">102</xref>], although some of the secondary metabolites such as THC and CBD have also been tracked in pollen [
 <xref rid="B35-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>], seeds [
 <xref rid="B103-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">103</xref>,
 <xref rid="B104-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">104</xref>], stem [
 <xref rid="B105-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">105</xref>,
 <xref rid="B106-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">106</xref>], leaves [
 <xref rid="B73-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">73</xref>,
 <xref rid="B106-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">106</xref>], and roots [
 <xref rid="B106-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">106</xref>] in a low quantity [
 <xref rid="B35-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>,
 <xref rid="B103-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">103</xref>,
 <xref rid="B107-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">107</xref>]. However, trichomes covering the female flower are the major site of phytocannabinoids production [
 <xref rid="B105-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">105</xref>,
 <xref rid="B106-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">106</xref>,
 <xref rid="B108-molecules-25-04036" ref-type="bibr">108</xref>].
</p>
